I. Fall Quarter: Exploratory Phase & LLM Domain Adaptation (Weeks 1–10) 

The research project was initiated to explore the intersection of Generative AI and Quantitative Finance, with a particular focus on the role of LLMs in market volatility analysis. The goal was to evaluate whether domain-specific LLMs could assist in identifying volatility patterns, early warning signals, and risk factors from multi-market datasets. 

Weeks 1–2: Framework Assessment 

Conducted a comparative analysis of open-source financial LLMs (FinGPT, FinBERT) against proprietary platforms such as BloombergGPT. 

Key research questions: 

Can Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) fine-tuning achieve high-fidelity financial signal extraction without full model retraining? 

Does Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) improve contextual understanding of historical market events while reducing inference overhead? 

Methods: Constructed benchmark queries on market data (e.g., volatility clustering, regime shifts) and compared outputs for consistency, signal relevance, and computational efficiency. 

Insight: LoRA allows targeted adaptation of large models with minimal additional parameters, making it feasible for our computational environment. 

Weeks 3–5: Technical Integration & Strategy Shift 

Explored multi-market correlation matrices, cross-asset interactions, and the mathematical foundations of option pricing (Black-Scholes, binomial trees). 

Discovered that LLM agents could quantify “market surprise”, essentially measuring deviations between expected and observed market returns. 

This observation motivated a shift from generic generative tasks to volatility-centric modeling, focusing on how market surprise signals could feed predictive models for risk management. 

Weeks 6–10: Infrastructure Development 

Developed automated data pipelines: 

Scraped market time series and derivative data using Alpha Vantage API. 

Employed Jina AI for document retrieval and knowledge embedding. 

Standardized preprocessing: missing data imputation, log-return transformation, and normalization. 

Outcome: By the end of Fall Quarter, a robust infrastructure for integrating real-time market signals into AI models was in place. 

Decision: Shift focus from purely generative LLM outputs to structured risk-assessment models, laying the groundwork for hybrid econometric–AI models. 

 

II. Winter Quarter: Specialization in Crude Oil Volatility (Weeks 1–5) 

Winter Quarter narrowed focus to WTI Crude Oil, chosen for its high volatility, pronounced stylized facts, and relevance to global financial stability. 

Winter Break & Week 1: Crisis Period Identification 

Selected testing windows: 

2007–09 Global Financial Crisis 

2020–21 COVID-19 Recession 

Justification: These periods exhibit extreme volatility features—volatility clustering, leptokurtosis (fat tails), and leverage effects—ideal for evaluating hybrid models. 

Weeks 2–4: Econometric Baseline & GARCH Variants 

Converted raw WTI prices to stationary log-returns to meet assumptions of GARCH-type models. 

Evaluated three GARCH specifications: 

sGARCH (symmetric): Models variance with equal response to positive and negative shocks. 

eGARCH / tGARCH (asymmetric): Captures leverage effect, where negative shocks increase future volatility more than positive shocks. 

Calibration: Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE) was used to fit each GARCH model to historical data. 

Observations: 

Asymmetric GARCH variants performed better during crisis periods. 

Standard GARCH struggled to capture extreme tail behavior in the 2020–21 COVID recession dataset. 

Week 5: Hybridization Methodology 

Transitioned to a hybrid ensemble approach: 

GARCH forecasts are transformed into feature inputs for neural networks. 

Ensures that both linear persistence (from GARCH) and non-linear patterns (from neural networks) are captured. 

Key considerations: 

Feature engineering involved rolling variance, residuals, and standardized shocks from GARCH models. 

Target variable: one-day-ahead volatility or Value-at-Risk (VaR) at 95% and 99% confidence levels. 

Preliminary results: Neural networks could exploit residual structures left by GARCH, improving predictive accuracy during crisis periods. 

 

III. Current Framework: GARCH-Time-MoE & AI Agency (Weeks 6–Present) 

Winter Quarter work has evolved toward integrating econometrics with Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) neural architectures, emphasizing adaptive weighting across volatility regimes. Focus is primarily on Goal 1, with Goal 2 (autonomous trading agent) planned but not actively pursued this quarter. 

1. Goal 1: GARCH–Time-MoE Hybrid Model 

Time-MoE Architecture 

Dynamically assigns weights to specialized expert networks depending on temporal volatility regimes (high, medium, low). 

Experts consist of LSTM layers trained on residuals from different GARCH variants, allowing the model to capture complex non-linear patterns beyond standard econometrics. 

GARCH-NN Equivalence 

Reinterpret GARCH(1,1) as a specialized RNN kernel: 

Recursive variance updates are encoded directly into network architecture. 

Ensures volatility signals influence predictions throughout the network rather than acting as post-hoc features. 

Progressive Residual Modeling 

Linear Modeling: Captures autocorrelations in returns. 

Time-MoE / LSTM Expert Layer: Models complex non-linear dependencies, leveraging multiple specialized expert networks to handle regime shifts. 

GARCH Layer: Fits residual volatility clusters to remaining errors, ensuring accurate tail-risk estimates. 

Training Strategy 

Loss function combines Mean Squared Error (MSE) for volatility prediction and VaR coverage penalties for tail risk performance. 

Training uses sliding windows over crisis periods to enforce robustness to regime shifts. 

Experts are dynamically weighted via a softmax gating network, where the gate learns which expert is most relevant at each timestep. 

Observations to Date 

Hybrid model consistently outperforms single GARCH and single LSTM baselines during periods of extreme volatility. 

Asymmetric GARCH-based residuals improve expert specialization in the MoE layer. 

Temporal gating allows the model to adjust expert influence across pre-crisis, crisis, and post-crisis phases. 

2. Goal 2: Autonomous AI Agent (Planned, Not Focused This Quarter) 

Concept: Use one-day-ahead VaR predictions to adjust positions in real-time. 

Agent will later be validated against Firm Loss Functions to penalize underestimation (risk exposure) or overestimation (capital opportunity cost). 

Currently deferred to prioritize full validation of Goal 1. 

 

IV. Evaluation & Validation 

Statistical Framework 

Coverage Tests: 

Unconditional Coverage (UC): Ensures VaR violation frequency matches nominal confidence levels. 

Conditional Coverage (CC): Checks for serial dependence of violations, ensuring model is not missing clusters of extreme events. 

Regulatory Loss Functions: 

Lopez Quadratic Loss (RQL): Penalizes magnitude of VaR violations. 

Caporin_1 (RC_1): Measures performance under extreme market conditions, emphasizing tail risk. 

Preliminary Findings 

Hybrid GARCH-Time-MoE models yield: 

Lower UC and CC test rejections during crises compared to baseline GARCH or LSTM models. 

Reduced predictive error for extreme volatility events. 

Better stability in rolling VaR forecasts, highlighting robustness to regime shifts. 
